<HEADLINE>
<P>
WANNA DANCE?: THERE'S PEER PLEASURE AT METROPOLIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROSE APODACA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Metropolis' newest gig, PleasureDome, may just be the sexiest young thing in 
the county. 
</P>
<P>
 From the pulsating grooves to many of the fashionable patrons, the Sunday-only 
event oozes with sex appeal. Beefy, Chippendales-like go-go dancers shake it on 
the go-go platforms, while screens show colorfully abstract videos of studly 
men, and another screen features a live shadow dancer. A state-of-the-art 
computerized light and sound system drenches the whole scene, which includes 
the distribution of free condoms, bearing the Metropolis logo, from 
CondomRevolution in Costa Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
 Healthy attendance at last week's opening reflected an open-minded mix of 
sexes and sexual preferences, unified for the sole reason of getting in one 
more night of partying before the weekend is officially over. 
</P>
<P>
 DJ Eddie-X of Los Angeles' Temple-fame rotates an infectious run of house 
music that -- as the crowd showed -- was hard to resist. Dance fools who 
haven't visited Metropolis in months because they didn't like the obtrusive 
posts that split up the dance floor will love the recent changes: The posts are 
gone, consolidating the area into an open space.  
</P>
<P>
 The go-going Fettish Boys, clad in very little, elicit tips from onlookers of 
both sexes. On opening night, one Fettish Boy dressed in an original Van Buren 
sequined wind-breaker and mesh top studded with the letters F, A, G. 
In-your-face fashion is always the most fabulous. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides the free condoms, you practitioners of social responsibility will 
appreciate that drinking beer here can actually help a local AIDS organization. 
Sunday marked the Metropolis debut of Pink Triangle, a micro-brewed light beer 
that, according to promotional cards on the club's tables, was "created for the 
nation's Lesbian and Gay Community." The Iowa-based brewery promises to donate 
no less than 25% of its profits to AIDS organizations in areas where the beer 
is sold.  
</P>
<P>
 Still, Pink Triangle didn't outdo the night's $2 drink specials of 16-ounce 
drafts of Bud, Coors Light and Miller Genuine Draft. After 9 p.m., the price of 
each rises to $3.25. Imported brews are $4 all night. Also at the bar: wells, 
$3.75; premiums, $4.25 to $5, and glasses of wine run $3.75 to 4.75. Bottled 
water and sodas are $2. 
</P>
<P>
 Metropolis's in-house sushi bar, Octopussy, serves it up from 7 to 11 p.m. 
Selections are $3 to $12. The kitchen also has available California cuisine, 
such as salads, pastas and sandwiches, $5 to $7. 
</P>
<P>
 Although the dance floor and main bar saw the greatest action on opening night 
(it took considerable patience to maneuver those areas or just to order a 
drink), the gorgeous rosewood pool tables were never wanting for players, even 
at $12 an hour. 
</P>
<P>
 Rose Apodaca is a free-lance writer who contributes regularly to The Times 
Orange County Edition.  
</P>
<P>
 * PLEASUREDOME 
</P>
<P>
 * At Metropolis, 4255 Campus Drive, Irvine.  
</P>
<P>
 * (714) 725-0300.  
</P>
<P>
 * Sundays only, 7 p.m. to 2 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 * Cover: $5. 
</P>
<P>
 MORE CLUBS: 
</P>
<P>
 Tango, at Mum's, 144 Pine Ave., Long Beach. (310) 437-7700. Fridays only, 9 
p.m. to 2 a.m. Cover: $10 (but passes are available). Hosted by Indigo 
Productions, Tango has all the energy, dress-to-impress attitude and cordial 
spirit of that outfit's other promotions, such as Thursday night disco at 
Roxbury South in Santa Ana. The mainstream dance pop doesn't earn the club any 
points in the music department (head on up to the roof to hear old school, new 
wave and classic KROQ), but with so many folks gettin' down and having a 
genuine good time, who's keeping score? Certainly not the stylish 
twentysomethings now packing the place. 
</P>
<P>
 Soul Shack at Club 5902, 5902 Warner Ave., Huntington Beach. (714) 840-6118. 
Sundays only, 9 p.m. to 2 a.m. Cover: $4. The musical fare at Soul Shack is 
decidedly fresh and too funky to sit out. Along with early rap, deejay Beej 
rotates a prime selection of rare groove vinyl (translated as '60s and '70s 
funk-heavy tracks) and acid jazz. Live bands also keep the dancers moving. 
All-night drink specials are a plus if the earlier part of the weekend just 
about emptied your wallet. 
</P>
<P>
 Mango, 353 E. Coast Highway, Newport Beach. (714) 673-7800. Open Tuesday 
through Saturday from 5:30 p.m. to 10 p.m. for dinner, club is open from 9:30 
p.m. to 2 a.m.; Sunday 1 p.m. to 2 a.m. Closed Monday. Cover: $5. This new hot 
spot seems plucked right out of Miami's trendy South Beach. It's a place where 
fans of cumbia, mambo, salsa, calypso and even New Orleans jazz can savor those 
rhythms, as furnished by an assortment of live bands. The dance floor is rather 
small, but bumping into and rubbing against other dancers is part of any decent 
salsa club scene.  
</P>
<P>
 Orange County's Music City, 18774 Brookhurst St., Fountain Valley. (714) 
963-2366. Open 7 p.m. to 2 a.m. Wednesday, Thursday and Saturday; 5 p.m. to 2 
a.m. Friday. No cover on Wednesdays and Thursdays; $5 cover after 8 p.m. on 
Fridays and Saturdays. This place used to be known as the Hop, a '50s and '60s 
nostalgia club owned by Righteous Brother Bill Medley. As Music City, it's 
entered a new era, focusing mostly on music of the '60s and '70s, though other 
eras still surface occasionally. Cover bands interpret their favorite oldies, 
alternating nights with the recorded versions.  
</P>
<P>
 Dante's, 1701 Corinthian Way, Newport Beach. (714) 955-3821. Open Monday and 
Tuesday 11 a.m. to 11:30 p.m., Wednesday and Thursday 11 a.m. to midnight, 
Friday 11 a.m. to 1:30 a.m., and Saturday 5 p.m. to 1:30 a.m. Closed Sundays. 
No cover. Newport Beach might be the last place you'd expect to label a hotbed 
of gypsy music, but it's here that the trio known as Vladamer, Grigorii and 
Misha perform Eastern European traditional tunes and vintage cabaret favorites. 
A small dance floor accommodates those who just can't contain themselves.  
</P>
<P>
 The Lord Nelson, 1464 S. Coast Highway, Laguna Beach. (714) 494-5707. Open 
daily at 11:30 a.m. Closing time varies Sunday through Thursday, depending on 
customers; open Friday and Saturday till 2 a.m. Cover: $1 on Thursday nights; 
$3 (occasionally more) on Friday and Saturday. Thursday nights at this 
English-style pub feature some of the most innovative programming in the 
county. That's when, in an evening dubbed the B-Side, deejay Tony Vick plays a 
mix of Brazilian, acid jazz, Arabic disco, hippie pop, glam, punk and just 
about anything else. Friday and Saturday nights feature live local bands for 
cheap, and the dinner menu features bangers and mash. Who could ask for more? 
</P>
<P>
 Electric Circus, 314 N. Beach Blvd., Anaheim. (714) 826-9686. Open daily, 4 
p.m. to 2 a.m. No cover Sunday through Tuesday and on Thursday; Wednesday is 
$3, $5 for ages 18 to 21; Friday and Saturday, $2-$3. This newly opened, 
6,500-square-foot venue is a diamond in the rough that could rank among the 
county's brightest party sites in '94. The decor is a mix of neo-baroque and 
industrial -- plush fabrics, Roman-style pillars, chipped concrete flooring. 
Even the nine billiards tables look elegant, topped in red felt. Unlike the 
yuppie clientele found at the county's other upscale pool hall nightclubs 
(Shark Club, Metropolis), Electric Circus attracts the kind of 18 and older 
scenesters who are often categorized under alternative.  
</P>
<P>
 The White House, 340 South Coast Highway, Laguna Beach. (714) 494-8088. Open 
Tuesday through Friday 7 a.m. to 2 a.m., Saturday through Monday 8 a.m. to 2 
a.m. Cover: varies, up to $4. More than two dozen Tiffany lamps hang through 
this narrow bar space, where a very long, varnished bar is crowded nightly with 
"locals" from near and far chatting over a glass of wine or a 16-ounce schooner 
of beer. Live rock and reggae bands play nightly, drawing a crowd of mostly 
twenty- to fortysomethings who continuously cram the small dance floor.  
</P>
<P>
 Tiki Bar, 1700 Placentia Ave., Costa Mesa. (714) 548-3533. Open daily, 11 a.m. 
to 2 a.m. Cover: $3 Thursday through Saturday. This 2,000-square-foot space 
(formerly the Newport Roadhouse) with a "Gilligan's Island"-type decor sits in 
an industrial spread that is home to some of the heavier hitters in the 
action-wear industry. So it comes as no surprise that the crowd here is 
generally clad in what would otherwise be worn on the beach or the slopes, and 
only a few patrons are over age 30. A dozen televisions continuously run surf, 
skateboard and snowboard videos, while a deejay spins everything from the 
Village People to Stone Temple Pilots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
