</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CANDIDATES FILE FOR JUNE 7 PRIMARY; GOP INFIGHTING DEVELOPS; POLITICS: ANAHEIM 
COUNCILMAN IRV PICKLER FILES FOR ASSEMBLY RACE. A REPUBLICAN FEUD SIMMERS OVER 
A 70TH ASSEMBLY CANDIDATE WHO IS NOT BACKED BY LAME DUCK GIL FERGUSON. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GEBE MARTINEZ, TIMES POLITICAL WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The June 7 primary election battle began taking shape Wednesday as candidates 
in state and judicial races met their first deadline to file their declarations 
to run. 
</P>
<P>
 Three of Orange County's incumbent Republicans will escape challenge in the 
primary, but the Democrats promised to give them a fight in the general 
election come November. 
</P>
<P>
 The Republicans facing no primary opposition are: Assemblyman Curt Pringle of 
Garden Grove in the 68th District; Assemblyman Mickey Conroy of Santa Ana in 
the 71st District, and Assemblyman Ross Johnson of Placentia in the 72nd 
district. 
</P>
<P>
 State Sen. William Craven (R-Oceanside) and 73rd District Assemblyman Bill 
Morrow (R-Oceanside), whose districts represent portions of south Orange 
County, also have no primary opponents. 
</P>
<P>
 Among those candidates creating a flurry of talk Wednesday was Anaheim 
Councilman Irv Pickler, who paid a $525 filing fee to hold a spot in the June 7 
Democratic Primary for the 68th Assembly District seat. 
</P>
<P>
 The races likely to draw the most attention are in the 69th and 70th Assembly 
districts, where the incumbents -- Assemblymen Tom Umberg (D-Garden Grove) and 
Gil Ferguson (R-Newport Beach) respectively -- are not seeking reelection. The 
filing deadline for those seats is extended until Monday. That is also the 
first day of filing for congressional candidates and nonpartisan county 
offices, such as the County Board of Supervisors, district attorney and 
sheriff-coroner. 
</P>
<P>
 A feud has already developed among Republicans over who will succeed Ferguson 
in 70th District, which is considered the most Republican Assembly district in 
the state. 
</P>
<P>
 Ferguson, who is stepping down for a possible run at the state Senate, accused 
state Sen. John R. Lewis (R-Orange) and Rep. Ed Royce (R-Fullerton) of being 
"self-anointed kingmakers" and endorsing Republican Phillip B. Greer, an Irvine 
attorney and one of at least four candidates seeking the GOP nomination in that 
race. 
</P>
<P>
 Ferguson would not say who will would be his choice for a successor, but he 
noted that it would not be Greer, a former Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
 "I cannot let these outsiders come in and dictate what's going on in this 
district," Ferguson said. "They know how I feel. They are constantly fooling 
around on elections. They have been doing this since high school, as I 
understand." 
</P>
<P>
 In a statement issued later, Lewis responded: "Gil Ferguson is a hypocrite. In 
1984, when he ran for the Assembly as a virtual unknown, I and other 
conservative legislators from outside that district endorsed him and helped 
elect him to office. According to Gil in 1984, we were dedicated public 
servants. But now we are outside meddlers." 
</P>
<P>
 Despite the rivalry, Orange County Republican Chairman Thomas A. Fuentes said 
the squabbling would not diminish the party's chances of winning the seat. 
</P>
<P>
 "None of that amounts to anything, because whoever the Republican nominee is, 
he is going to win the election," Fuentes predicted. 
</P>
<P>
 Even though Democrats are fielding candidates in the major Assembly and state 
Senate races, Fuentes said their efforts would be futile. 
</P>
<P>
 As of the end of January, Republicans made up 52.3% of the registered voters 
in Orange County, compared to 34.4% for Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Democratic Party is essentially impotent in Orange County," Fuentes said. 
He noted that the Democrats' internal battle in the 69th Assembly District, 
which Umberg is leaving to run for state attorney general, could cause them to 
lose the only Orange County legislative seat they now hold. 
</P>
<P>
 But Orange County Democratic Chairwoman Dorianne Garcia predicted that her 
party will do better than expected because, unlike previous years, candidates 
were not recruited this year simply to put "warm bodies" on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we have great opportunities to get Democrats elected into Orange 
County elective offices this year," she said. "Democrats have been given a bum 
rap." 
</P>
<P>
 Garcia said the party is going to focus on the central Orange County districts 
where Democratic voter registration is highest. 
</P>
<P>
 The targeted districts include the 46th Congressional District now held by 
Rep. Robert K. Dornan (R-Garden Grove), the 68th and 69th Assembly districts, 
and the 34th state Senate District, which is being sought by Sen. Rob Hurtt of 
Garden Grove. Hurtt is currently listed as the senator for the 32nd District, 
which was redrawn and ended up in Los Angeles County. 
</P>
<P>
 Garcia said that money initially raised to defeat Dornan will be spread among 
those four targeted races. As of the end of the year, the "Beat Bob" 
fund-raising totaled $40,000. 
</P>
<P>
 The Democratic chairwoman noted that in the 1992 contest in the 68th Assembly 
District, Democrat Linda Kay Rigney received 44% of the vote against Pringle. 
</P>
<P>
 Although Pickler declared his intention to challenge Pringle in the 68th 
Assembly District, he said he is not sure he will stay in the race and will 
decide before the March 11 deadline to file final nomination papers. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was looking at supervisor, I was looking at mayor, and at the Assembly 
district," Pickler said at the county registrar of voters office. 
</P>
<P>
 But, said Pickler, with his "good friend" Tom Daly now in the Anaheim mayor's 
seat, he is "leaning" toward the Assembly race. 
</P>
<P>
 Pringle said he would take a challenge from Pickler or any other Democrat 
"very seriously." But he remained confident he would prevail in November, 
suggesting that the race would come down to "a very clear-cut distinction 
between ideals" on issues such as taxes and big government. 
</P>
<P>
 Firing his first salvo of the campaign, Pringle noted that Pickler supported 
utility tax increases in Anaheim. "I oppose tax increases and have consistently 
done so in Sacramento," he said. "Irv Pickler has supported taxes." 
</P>
<P>
 Times staff writers Eric Lichtblau and Eric Bailey contributed to this report. 
Primary Election Filings  
</P>
