<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: LYNWOOD; RUNOFF ELECTION TUESDAY FOR SCHOOL BOARD SEAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Voters will attempt to break a tie Tuesday between two incumbents for a seat 
on the Lynwood Unified School District board. 
</P>
<P>
 A special election is being held to decide whether incumbent Rachel Chavez or 
Joe T. Battle will serve another term.Each received 1,281 votes in the Nov. 2 
school board race, just behind newcomer Laura M. Byrd. The three were competing 
for two seats. Byrd was sworn into office in December. Trustees decided on a 
special runoff to break the tie between Chavez and Battle, but will allow both 
incumbents to remain until then. The decision temporarily left the district 
with six board members. 
</P>
<P>
 Chavez, 55, a homemaker, former adult education teacher and the board's only 
Latina, has served one term. Battle, 52, an Internal Revenue Service manager, 
is seeking his fourth term. 
</P>
<P>
 Polls will be open from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. 
