NATION IN BRIEF; CONNECTICUT; WEICKER URGES END TO PROPERTY TAXES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Connecticut's three-year-old income tax has boosted the state's revenues so 
much that Gov. Lowell P. Weicker Jr. proposed eliminating property taxes within 
10 years. The proposal would save $700 million a year for taxpayers in 
Connecticut, where property taxes are among the highest in the United States.In 
his State of the State Address in Hartford, Weicker said cities and towns would 
be reimbursed from state funds for income lost through elimination of the 
property tax. The proposal's chance of passing the Legislature is unclear. 
Weicker's speech came a day after the U.S. Census Bureau said three of the top 
10 fastest-shrinking cities in the nation are in Connecticut. Economists said 
people are leaving because of poor job opportunities and high taxes. 
</P>
