<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL NEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ELSEWHERE 
</P>
<P>
 AZUSA: The City Council voted to pay off an $88,000 mortgage and $5,000 in 
interest owed by Peregrinos De Emaus so that the homeless shelter can raise 
money to bring the property up to city building codes. 
</P>
<P>
 COVINA: The City Council decided to keep the city afloat financially by using 
most of the money in a reserve fund. The council voted last week to remove 
$1.75 million -- roughly the deficit for this fiscal year -- from a fund used 
to replace and repair city equipment. One official said the $537,000 left in 
that fund is insufficient to cover anticipated costs. 
</P>
<P>
 LA CANADA FLINTRIDGE: The City Council turned down a request from the Descanso 
Gardens Guild for a $200,000 loan to cover deficits and help complete a 
$1.5-million rose garden.  
</P>
<P>
 LA VERNE: The city has won a state transportation grant of nearly $140,000 to 
spruce up Arrow Highway between E Street and San Dimas Canyon Road. The city is 
seeking volunteers to help plant trees and shrubs along the road in April. 
Information: (909) 596-8706. 
</P>
<P>
 ROSEMEAD: The City Council passed a resolution opposing a plan by two water 
districts to "drought-proof" the San Gabriel Valley by replenishing its 
underground drinking water supply with highly treated sewage water. 
</P>
<P>
 SIERRA MADRE: The city narrowed the field for police chief to three Southland 
candidates: Lt. Edwin A. Jakoala, 51, of the Palos Verdes Estates Police 
Department; Sgt. Robert K. Petitt, 47, and Lt. Joseph R. Surgent, 51, both of 
the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department. 
</P>
<P>
 SOUTH PASADENA: The City Council asked the city attorney to draft a resolution 
to place a library tax on the June 7 ballot. The tax on a 2,000-square-foot 
home would cost $24 a year. 
</P>
<P>
 TEMPLE CITY: The City Council turned down for now the gift of the 1903 Teagle 
House for use as a historical museum because of the $100,000 cost of relocating 
it from San Gabriel. 
</P>
<P>
 WEST COVINA: In an effort to boost ridership, the City Council approved a $20 
subsidy for residents who ride the Metrolink trains to jobs in downtown Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
