<HEADLINE>
<P>
EDUCATION; COMMUNITY SERVICE PLAN FOR STUDENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Temple City high school students will be required to perform 100 hours of 
community service in order to graduate, under a new policy that was expected to 
be passed Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
 The policy would make Temple City Unified School District one of a handful in 
the state and the second in the county to make such service mandatory. 
</P>
<P>
 For more than a decade, South Pasadena Unified School District has required 45 
hours of community service for graduation. 
</P>
<P>
 In Temple City, students will be required to donate 30 hours of service in 
each of their first two years of high school and 20 hours of service each year 
as a junior and senior. 
</P>
<P>
 Janice Murasko, program author and district service coordinator, has lined up 
opportunities such as teaching English as a second language, working with the 
U.S. Forest Service or making home repairs for senior citizens. Students also 
can propose their own ideas, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 "Studies show gang activity and dropout rates go down and test scores go up in 
states and cities that have tried this," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021094-0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 012212 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
