<P>
San Gabriel Valley; Part J; Page 6 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
450 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRANSPORTATION; 21 FREEWAY STRUCTURES IN VALLEY NEED RETROFITTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Caltrans data show that 21 freeway bridges, interchanges and connector roads 
in the San Gabriel Valley are still too weak to withstand a strong earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
 After the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake in the Bay Area, Caltrans in 1990 
identified road structures statewide that needed retrofitting because the 
columns supporting them tend to fracture in a quake. Caltrans scheduled 243 
structures in Los Angeles County for quake strengthening, 48 of them in the San 
Gabriel Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 Four years later, 27 of those 48 retrofits have been completed and work is in 
progress on seven more. However, construction contracts have yet to be awarded 
for 14 structures in the region. Under a 1990 state law, all contracts were to 
have been awarded by the end of 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 The San Gabriel Valley retrofits are slightly ahead of neighboring Southland 
regions. Countywide 44% of the overpasses that need to be retrofitted are 
complete, compared with 56% in the valley. 
</P>
<P>
 The need to retrofit took on new urgency after the Jan. 17 Northridge quake. 
Ten of the 11 roadways that collapsed in that quake were scheduled for 
strengthening. The 11th was not on the list. All of the 106 county overpasses 
that had been retrofitted survived the temblor. 
</P>
<P>
 Caltrans' chief engineer, James. E. Roberts, has called for the program to be 
put on an emergency schedule that allows for quicker awarding of contracts. 
Roberts said a court dispute with a union delayed retrofitting. 
</P>
<P>
 Critics of Caltrans maintain that the transportation agency has wasted time 
and money building freeways before securing old ones. Each bridge costs 
approximately $500,000 to retrofit and takes a year. Road Work 
</P>
<P>
 The 21 road structures where retrofit has not been completed:  
</P>
